==Old English==
===Etymology===
From Germanic: cognate with Old Frisian [[barch]] (Frisian [[baerg]]), Old Saxon [[barug]] (Dutch [[barg]]), Old High German [[barug]] (dialectal German [[Barch]]), Old Norse {{Latinx|[[bǫrgr]]}}.

===Pronunciation===
[[IPA]]: /bæarg/

===Noun===
'''bearg''' ''m''
# a castrated boar, a [[barrow]]
#:''Amæsted swin, bearg bellende on boc-wuda'': a fattened pig, a barrow grunting in beech woods.  (''Codex Exoniensis'')


